  "prompt": "How are belly buttons formed?",
  "response": "Belly buttons, or navels, are formed during fetal development. Here's a brief explanation:\n\n1. When a baby is in the womb, it is connected to the mother through the umbilical cord, which provides nutrients and oxygen.\n\n2. The umbilical cord connects to the placenta and passes through the baby's abdomen, connecting to the developing digestive system.\n\n3. After birth, the umbilical cord is cut, leaving a small stump that eventually dries up and falls off within a few weeks.\n\n4. The area where the umbilical cord was attached heals and creates a small scar, which becomes the belly button.\n\n5. The shape and depth of the belly button (innie or outie) depend on how the skin and underlying tissues heal after the cord falls off.\n\nThe belly button is essentially a remnant of the connection between the baby and its mother during pregnancy, serving as a permanent reminder of this early life connection.",
